\nsong_index = build_song_index()\n\nnoise_files = []\nfor root, _, files in os.walk(ESC_PATH):\n    for f in files:\n        if f.endswith('.wav'):\n            noise_files.append(os.path.join(root, f))\n\nprint(f\"\\nNoise files available: {len(noise_files)}\")","metadata":{},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 8. Train / Validation Split\n\nSplit each genre's songs 85% / 15% for training and validation respectively. The split is done per-genre to ensure all genres are represented in both sets (stratified split). After the split, `train_index` and `val_index` are used by the dataset classes below.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"train_index = {}\nval_index   = {}\n\nfor genre in GENRES:\n    songs = song_index[genre][:]\n    random.shuffle(songs)\n    split = int(0.85 * len(songs))\n    train_index[genre] = songs[:split]\n    val_index[genre]   = songs[split:]\n    print(f\"  {genre:<12} -> Train: {len(train_index[genre])}, Val: {len(val_index[genre])}\")\n\nprint(\"\\nTrain/Val split complete.\")","metadata":{},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 9. Audio Augmentation Pipeline\n\nThe augmentation functions below are applied to each training sample on-the-fly. This means every epoch sees slightly different versions of the audio, effectively multiplying the dataset diversity.\n\nThe pipeline (applied in order for each stem) is:\n\n1. **Random crop** — take a random 25-second window from the audio. Different crops of the same song expose different musical segments to the model.\n2. **Tempo stretch** — speed up or slow down by up to ±12% using `librosa.effects.time_stretch`. This is a well-established augmentation for music tasks that changes rhythmic feel without altering pitch.\n3. **Pitch shift** — shift pitch by ±2 semitones using `librosa.effects.pitch_shift`. Music genre is pitch-invariant, so a blues track remains blues regardless of its key. This augmentation is specifically recommended for music classification tasks (Javanmardi et al., 2024; Park et al., 2019).\n4. **Random gain** — scale volume randomly between 0.7x and 1.3x. Simulates recordings at different levels.\n5. **Stem weight** — multiply each stem by a random weight (0.6–1.4) before mixing. This creates varied spectral balances: some mixes are vocals-heavy, others percussion-heavy.\n\nAfter mixing all four stems:\n\n6. **Normalise** — scale to unit peak amplitude.\n7. **ESC-50 noise** — add a random environmental noise clip at 3–20% of the signal level. This simulates real-world mashup recordings.\n8. **Re-normalise** — scale again after noise addition.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"def load_audio(path):\n    audio, _ = librosa.load(path, sr=SAMPLE_RATE, mono=True)\n    return audio.astype(np.float32)\n\ndef normalize(audio):\n    return audio / (np.max(np.abs(audio)) + 1e-6)\n\ndef crop_random(audio):\n    if len(audio) >= MAX_LENGTH:\n        start = random.randint(0, len(audio) - MAX_LENGTH)\n        return audio[start : start + MAX_LENGTH]\n    return np.pad(audio, (0, MAX_LENGTH - len(audio)))\n\ndef crop_center(audio):\n    if len(audio) >= MAX_LENGTH:\n        start = (len(audio) - MAX_LENGTH) // 2\n        return audio[start : start + MAX_LENGTH]\n    return np.pad(audio, (0, MAX_LENGTH - len(audio)))\n\ndef random_gain(audio):\n    return audio * random.uniform(0.7, 1.3)\n\ndef tempo_augment(audio):\n    if random.random() < TEMPO_PROB:\n        rate  = random.uniform(*TEMPO_RANGE)\n        audio = librosa.effects.time_stretch(audio, rate=rate)\n    return audio\n\ndef pitch_augment(audio):\n    if random.random() < PITCH_PROB:\n        n_steps = random.uniform(*PITCH_RANGE)\n        audio   = librosa.effects.pitch_shift(y=audio, sr=SAMPLE_RATE, n_steps=n_steps)\n    return audio\n\ndef add_noise(audio):\n    if random.random() < NOISE_PROB and len(noise_files) > 0:\n        noise = load_audio(random.choice(noise_files))\n        noise = crop_random(noise)\n        level = random.uniform(*NOISE_LEVEL)\n        audio = audio + level * noise\n    return audio\n\ndef polarity_invert(audio):\n    if random.random() < 0.5:\n        return -audio\n    return audio\n\nprint(\"Audio augmentation functions defined.\")","metadata":{},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 10. AST Feature Extractor and Model\n\nWe load the pre-trained `MIT/ast-finetuned-audioset-10-10-0.4593` model with its original 527-class head replaced by a fresh 10-class head for our GTZAN genres. The `ignore_mismatched_sizes=True` flag handles this head replacement.\n\nThe `ASTFeatureExtractor` converts raw waveforms into log-mel spectrograms normalised to the AudioSet mean and standard deviation — the same normalisation used during pre-training. This is important: the HuggingFace documentation explicitly recommends using this extractor rather than computing mel features manually, to stay consistent with the pre-training input distribution.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"MODEL_NAME = 'MIT/ast-finetuned-audioset-10-10-0.4593'\n\nfeature_extractor = ASTFeatureExtractor.from_pretrained(MODEL_NAME)\nprint(\"Feature extractor loaded.\")\n\nmodel = ASTForAudioClassification.from_pretrained(\n    MODEL_NAME,\n    num_labels              = NUM_LABELS,\n    id2label                = id2label,\n    label2id                = label2id,\n    ignore_mismatched_sizes = True\n)\nmodel.to(DEVICE)\n\ntotal_params = sum(p.numel() for p in model.parameters())\nprint(f\"AST model loaded on {DEVICE}.\")\nprint(f\"Total parameters: {total_params:,}\")","metadata":{},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 11. Dataset Classes\n\n**TrainDataset** generates `TRAIN_SIZE` synthetic mashup samples on-the-fly. For each sample, it:\n- Picks a random genre\n- Samples each of the four stems from potentially *different* songs within that genre (cross-song mixing)\n- Applies the full augmentation pipeline to each stem individually before mixing\n- Feeds the mixed waveform through `ASTFeatureExtractor` to get the log-mel spectrogram tensor\n\nBecause samples are generated dynamically, every training epoch sees a different random combination of stems, crops, and augmentations.\n\n**ValDataset** loads the actual song stems using a deterministic centre-crop and no augmentation, so validation F1 scores are comparable across epochs.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"class TrainDataset(Dataset):\n\n    def __init__(self, song_index, feature_extractor, size=TRAIN_SIZE):\n        self.song_index        = song_index\n        self.feature_extractor = feature_extractor\n        self.size              = size\n\n    def __len__(self):\n        return self.size\n\n    def __getitem__(self, idx):\n        while True:\n            try:\n                genre = random.choice(GENRES)\n                songs = self.song_index[genre]\n                if len(songs) == 0:\n                    continue\n\n                mixed = None\n                for stem in REQUIRED_STEMS:\n                    song_path = random.choice(songs)\n                    audio     = load_audio(os.path.join(song_path, stem))\n                    audio     = crop_random(audio)\n                    audio     = tempo_augment(audio)\n                    audio     = pitch_augment(audio)\n                    audio     = random_gain(audio)\n                    weight    = random.uniform(*STEM_WEIGHT_RANGE)\n                    audio     = audio * weight\n                    mixed = audio if mixed is None else mixed + audio\n\n                mixed = normalize(mixed)\n                mixed = polarity_invert(mixed)\n                mixed = add_noise(mixed)\n                mixed = normalize(mixed)\n\n                inputs = self.feature_extractor(\n                    mixed,\n                    sampling_rate  = SAMPLE_RATE,\n                    return_tensors = 'pt'\n                )\n                return {\n                    'input_values': inputs['input_values'].squeeze(0),\n                    'labels'      : torch.tensor(label2id[genre], dtype=torch.long)\n                }\n            except Exception:\n                continue\n\nprint(\"TrainDataset class defined.\")","metadata":{},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"class ValDataset(Dataset):\n\n    def __init__(self, song_index, feature_extractor):\n        self.feature_extractor = feature_extractor\n        self.samples = []\n        for genre in GENRES:\n            for song_path in song_index[genre]:\n                self.samples.append((genre, song_path))\n\n    def __len__(self):\n        return len(self.samples)\n\n    def __getitem__(self, idx):\n        genre, song_path = self.samples[idx]\n        mixed = None\n        for stem in REQUIRED_STEMS:\n            audio = load_audio(os.path.join(song_path, stem))\n            audio = crop_center(audio)\n            mixed = audio if mixed is None else mixed + audio\n\n        mixed  = normalize(mixed)\n        inputs = self.feature_extractor(\n            mixed,\n            sampling_rate  = SAMPLE_RATE,\n            return_tensors = 'pt'\n        )\n        return {\n            'input_values': inputs['input_values'].squeeze(0),\n            'labels'      : torch.tensor(label2id[genre], dtype=torch.long)\n        }\n\nprint(\"ValDataset class defined.\")","metadata":{},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 12. DataLoaders\n\nInstantiate the datasets and wrap them in PyTorch `DataLoader` objects. `pin_memory=True` and `persistent_workers=True` speed up CPU-to-GPU data transfer on Kaggle's hardware.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"train_dataset = TrainDataset(train_index, feature_extractor, size=TRAIN_SIZE)\nval_dataset   = ValDataset(val_index, feature_extractor)\n\ntrain_loader = DataLoader(\n    train_dataset,\n    batch_size         = BATCH_SIZE,\n    shuffle            = True,\n    num_workers        = NUM_WORKERS,\n    pin_memory         = True,\n    persistent_workers = True\n)\nval_loader = DataLoader(\n    val_dataset,\n    batch_size         = BATCH_SIZE,\n    shuffle            = False,\n    num_workers        = NUM_WORKERS,\n    pin_memory         = True,\n    persistent_workers = True\n)\n\nprint(f\"Train samples : {len(train_dataset)}\")\nprint(f\"Val samples   : {len(val_dataset)}\")\nprint(f\"Train batches : {len(train_loader)}\")\nprint(f\"Val batches   : {len(val_loader)}\")","metadata":{},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 13. Loss Function and Evaluation Metric\n\nWe use Cross-Entropy loss with `label_smoothing=0.1`. Label smoothing is a regularisation technique that prevents the model from becoming overconfident on training labels — instead of targeting a hard 0/1 probability, the target is softened to 0.1/0.9. This generally improves generalisation on downstream data.\n\nThe evaluation metric is Macro F1, averaged equally across all 10 genre classes. Macro F1 is appropriate here because it treats each class equally regardless of how many samples it has.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"criterion = nn.CrossEntropyLoss(label_smoothing=0.1)\nf1_metric = MulticlassF1Score(\n    num_classes = NUM_LABELS,\n    average     = 'macro'\n).to(DEVICE)\n\nprint(\"Loss : CrossEntropyLoss  (label_smoothing=0.1)\")\nprint(\"Metric: Macro F1 Score across 10 classes\")","metadata":{},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 14. Training and Validation Loop Functions\n\n`train_one_epoch` runs one full pass over the training loader. It uses **gradient accumulation**: gradients are accumulated over `GRAD_ACCUM` steps before performing a single optimiser update. This simulates a larger batch size without requiring more GPU memory. Gradient clipping (`max_norm=1.0`) prevents exploding gradients during fine-tuning.\n\n`validate` runs over the validation loader in inference mode (no gradients). It returns the Macro F1 score used for early stopping and checkpoint selection.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"def train_one_epoch(model, loader, optimizer, scheduler):\n    model.train()\n    f1_metric.reset()\n    total_loss = 0\n    optimizer.zero_grad()\n\n    for step, batch in enumerate(tqdm(loader, desc='Training')):\n        input_values = batch['input_values'].to(DEVICE)\n        labels       = batch['labels'].to(DEVICE)\n\n        outputs = model(input_values=input_values)\n        loss    = criterion(outputs.logits, labels) / GRAD_ACCUM\n        loss.backward()\n\n        if (step + 1) % GRAD_ACCUM == 0:\n            torch.nn.utils.clip_grad_norm_(model.parameters(), 1.0)\n            optimizer.step()\n            scheduler.step()\n            optimizer.zero_grad()\n\n        total_loss += loss.item() * GRAD_ACCUM\n        preds = torch.argmax(outputs.logits, dim=1)\n        f1_metric.update(preds, labels)\n\n    return total_loss / len(loader), f1_metric.compute().item()\n\n\ndef validate(model, loader):\n    model.eval()\n    f1_metric.reset()\n    with torch.no_grad():\n        for batch in tqdm(loader, desc='Validation'):\n            input_values = batch['input_values'].to(DEVICE)\n            labels       = batch['labels'].to(DEVICE)\n            outputs      = model(input_values=input_values)\n            preds        = torch.argmax(outputs.logits, dim=1)\n            f1_metric.update(preds, labels)\n    return f1_metric.compute().item()\n\nprint(\"train_one_epoch and validate functions ready.\")","metadata":{},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 15. Phase 1 — Classifier Head Warm-Up\n\nIn Phase 1, the entire AST backbone is frozen and only the new 10-class classification head is trained.\n\n**Why this matters:** The backbone was pre-trained on AudioSet with a 527-class head. We replaced that head with randomly-initialised 10-class weights. If we immediately fine-tune all layers with a large learning rate, the random gradients from the new head will corrupt the carefully-learned backbone representations. By warming up the head first, we ensure the classification layer produces meaningful gradients before the backbone starts adapting.\n\nPhase 1 uses a relatively high learning rate (`LR_P1 = 3e-4`) because there is no risk of destroying anything — the backbone is frozen. Early stopping with `PATIENCE_P1 = 2` prevents the head from overfitting before Phase 2 begins.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"for param in model.base_model.parameters():\n    param.requires_grad = False\n\ntrainable = sum(p.numel() for p in model.parameters() if p.requires_grad)\nprint(f\"Phase 1: {trainable:,} trainable parameters (classifier head only)\")\n\noptimizer_p1   = torch.optim.AdamW(\n    filter(lambda p: p.requires_grad, model.parameters()),\n    lr           = LR_P1,\n    weight_decay = WEIGHT_DECAY\n)\ntotal_steps_p1 = (len(train_loader) // GRAD_ACCUM) * EPOCHS_P1\nscheduler_p1   = get_cosine_schedule_with_warmup(\n    optimizer_p1,\n    num_warmup_steps   = total_steps_p1 // 10,\n    num_training_steps = total_steps_p1\n)\n\nbest_p1_f1   = 0\npatience_cnt = 0\n\nprint(f\"\\n{'='*55}\")\nprint(f\"PHASE 1 — Classifier Warm-Up  ({EPOCHS_P1} epochs max)\")\nprint(f\"{'='*55}\\n\")\n\nfor epoch in range(EPOCHS_P1):\n    train_loss, train_f1 = train_one_epoch(model, train_loader, optimizer_p1, scheduler_p1)\n    val_f1 = validate(model, val_loader)\n\n    print(f\"Epoch {epoch+1}/{EPOCHS_P1}\")\n    print(f\"  Train Loss : {train_loss:.4f}\")\n    print(f\"  Train F1   : {train_f1:.4f}\")\n    print(f\"  Val F1     : {val_f1:.4f}\")\n\n    if val_f1 > best_p1_f1:\n        best_p1_f1 = val_f1\n        torch.save(model.state_dict(), '/kaggle/working/best_model_phase1.pth')\n        patience_cnt = 0\n        print(f\"  Saved best Phase 1 model  (val F1: {best_p1_f1:.4f})\")\n    else:\n        patience_cnt += 1\n        if patience_cnt >= PATIENCE_P1:\n            print(\"  Early stopping Phase 1.\")\n            break\n\nprint(f\"\\nPhase 1 complete. Best val F1: {best_p1_f1:.4f}\")","metadata":{},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 16. Phase 2 — Full Fine-Tuning\n\nIn Phase 2, all layers are unfrozen and fine-tuned end-to-end.\n\nWe load the best checkpoint saved in Phase 1 and unfreeze every parameter. We then apply **layer-wise learning rates**: the backbone receives `LR_P2 = 1e-5` (very small, to preserve pre-trained features) while the classification head receives `LR_P2 * 10 = 1e-4` (larger, since it still needs to adapt). This asymmetric learning rate strategy is standard practice when fine-tuning large pre-trained transformers and is recommended in the AST paper (Gong et al., 2021).\n\nThe cosine schedule with 10% warm-up steps gently raises then decays the learning rate over the full Phase 2 training run. Early stopping with `PATIENCE_P2 = 4` gives the model enough time to improve while guarding against overfitting.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"model.load_state_dict(torch.load('/kaggle/working/best_model_phase1.pth'))\n\nfor param in model.parameters():\n    param.requires_grad = True\n\ntotal_params = sum(p.numel() for p in model.parameters())\nprint(f\"All {total_params:,} parameters unfrozen.\")\n\noptimizer_p2 = torch.optim.AdamW([\n    {'params': model.base_model.parameters(),  'lr': LR_P2},\n    {'params': model.classifier.parameters(),  'lr': LR_P2 * LR_HEAD_MULT},\n], weight_decay=WEIGHT_DECAY)\n\ntotal_steps_p2 = (len(train_loader) // GRAD_ACCUM) * EPOCHS_P2\nscheduler_p2   = get_cosine_schedule_with_warmup(\n    optimizer_p2,\n    num_warmup_steps   = total_steps_p2 // 10,\n    num_training_steps = total_steps_p2\n)\n\nbest_p2_f1   = 0\npatience_cnt = 0\n\nprint(f\"\\n{'='*55}\")\nprint(f\"PHASE 2 — Full Fine-Tune  ({EPOCHS_P2} epochs max)\")\nprint(f\"Base LR: {LR_P2}  |  Head LR: {LR_P2 * LR_HEAD_MULT}\")\nprint(f\"{'='*55}\\n\")\n\nfor epoch in range(EPOCHS_P2):\n    train_loss, train_f1 = train_one_epoch(model, train_loader, optimizer_p2, scheduler_p2)\n    val_f1 = validate(model, val_loader)\n\n    print(f\"Epoch {epoch+1}/{EPOCHS_P2}\")\n    print(f\"  Train Loss : {train_loss:.4f}\")\n    print(f\"  Train F1   : {train_f1:.4f}\")\n    print(f\"  Val F1     : {val_f1:.4f}\")\n\n    if val_f1 > best_p2_f1:\n        best_p2_f1 = val_f1\n        torch.save(model.state_dict(), '/kaggle/working/best_model_phase2.pth')\n        patience_cnt = 0\n        print(f\"  Saved best Phase 2 model  (val F1: {best_p2_f1:.4f})\")\n    else:\n        patience_cnt += 1\n        if patience_cnt >= PATIENCE_P2:\n            print(\"  Early stopping Phase 2.\")\n            break\n\nprint(f\"\\nPhase 2 complete. Best val F1: {best_p2_f1:.4f}\")","metadata":{},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 17. Test-Time Augmentation (TTA)\n\nAt inference time, instead of predicting from a single centre-crop of each test audio file, we take `N_TTA = 7` independent random crops, run each through the model, and **average the softmax probability vectors**. The final predicted class is the argmax of the averaged probabilities.\n\nThis works because each crop sees a slightly different temporal segment of the audio. Averaging over multiple crops reduces prediction variance — essentially an ensemble over crops of the same file. TTA consistently produces a higher Kaggle leaderboard score than the validation F1, because the test set contains similar messy mashup structures and TTA smooths out any unlucky single-crop predictions.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"def predict_with_tta(model, audio, n_tta=N_TTA):\n    all_probs = []\n    for _ in range(n_tta):\n        cropped = crop_random(audio)\n        cropped = normalize(cropped)\n        inputs  = feature_extractor(\n            cropped,\n            sampling_rate  = SAMPLE_RATE,\n            return_tensors = 'pt'\n        )\n        input_values = inputs['input_values'].to(DEVICE)\n        with torch.no_grad():\n            outputs = model(input_values=input_values)\n            probs   = torch.softmax(outputs.logits, dim=1)\n            all_probs.append(probs.cpu().numpy())\n\n    avg_probs = np.mean(all_probs, axis=0)\n    return np.argmax(avg_probs, axis=1)[0]\n\nprint(f\"TTA function ready. Using {N_TTA} crops per prediction.\")","metadata":{},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 18. Generate Submission\n\nLoad the best Phase 2 checkpoint and run TTA inference over all rows in `test.csv`. Each test file is loaded as a raw waveform, and `predict_with_tta` returns the final integer class index which we convert back to a genre string using `id2label`.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"model.load_state_dict(torch.load('/kaggle/working/best_model_phase2.pth'))\nmodel.eval()\nprint(f\"Best Phase 2 model loaded. Val F1 was: {best_p2_f1:.4f}\")\n\ntest_df   = pd.read_csv(os.path.join(BASE_PATH, 'test.csv'))\nprint(f\"Test samples: {len(test_df)}\")\n\nall_ids   = []\nall_preds = []\n\nfor idx in tqdm(range(len(test_df)), desc=f'TTA Inference (x{N_TTA})'):\n    row   = test_df.iloc[idx]\n    path  = os.path.join(BASE_PATH, row['filename'])\n    audio = load_audio(path)\n    pred  = predict_with_tta(model, audio, n_tta=N_TTA)\n    all_ids.append(row['id'])\n    all_preds.append(id2label[pred])\n\nsubmission = pd.DataFrame({'id': all_ids, 'genre': all_preds})\nsubmission.to_csv('/kaggle/working/submission.csv', index=False)\n\nprint(f\"\\nSubmission saved to /kaggle/working/submission.csv\")\nprint(f\"Total predictions : {len(submission)}\")\nprint(f\"\\nPredicted genre distribution:\")\nprint(submission['genre'].value_counts().to_string())\nprint(f\"\\nFirst 5 rows:\")\nprint(submission.head().to_string())","metadata":{},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 19. Training Summary",